### Define Textual App with Screens and CSS

Source: https://textual.textualize.io/blog/2022/11/26/on-dog-food-the-original-metaverse-and-not-being-bored

This Python snippet demonstrates the basic structure of a Textual application. It defines the CSS file, application title, and registers multiple screens ('main' and 'region'). The 'on_mount' method is used to push the initial 'main' screen when the application starts. This pattern is suitable for non-trivial applications where specific functionality is best encapsulated within dedicated screens.

```python
class GridInfo( App[ None ] ):
    """TUI app for showing information about the Second Life grid."""

    CSS_PATH = "gridinfo.css"
    """The name of the CSS file for the app."""

    TITLE = "Grid Information"
    """str: The title of the application."""

    SCREENS = {
        "main": Main,
        "region": RegionInfo
    }
    """The collection of application screens."""

    def on_mount( self ) -> None:
        """Set up the application on startup."""
        self.push_screen( "main" )

```

