### All Width Formats Example (Python & Textual CSS)

Source: https://textual.textualize.io/styles/width

This example showcases various width units in Textualize, including cells, percentages, viewport units (vw, vh), `fr` units, and `auto`. It uses `Placeholder` widgets with different width settings and a `Ruler` widget for visual reference. The Python code sets up the app and its composition, while the CSS defines the specific width values for each placeholder.

```python
from textual.app import App
from textual.containers import Horizontal
from textual.widgets import Label, Placeholder, Static


class Ruler(Static):
    def compose(self):
        ruler_text = "ยทยทยทยทโข" * 100
        yield Label(ruler_text)


class WidthComparisonApp(App):
    CSS_PATH = "width_comparison.tcss"

    def compose(self):
        yield Horizontal(
            Placeholder(id="cells"),
            Placeholder(id="percent"),
            Placeholder(id="w"),
            Placeholder(id="h"),
            Placeholder(id="vw"),
            Placeholder(id="vh"),
            Placeholder(id="auto"),
            Placeholder(id="fr1"),
            Placeholder(id="fr3"),
        )
        yield Ruler()


if __name__ == "__main__":
    app = WidthComparisonApp()
    app.run()


```

```textualcss
#cells {
    width: 9;
}
#percent {
    width: 12.5%;
}
#w {
    width: 10w;
}
#h {
    width: 25h;
}
#vw {
    width: 15vw;
}
#vh {
    width: 25vh;
}
#auto {
    width: auto;
}
#fr1 {
    width: 1fr;
}
#fr3 {
    width: 3fr;
}

Screen {
    layers: ruler;
}

Ruler {
    layer: ruler;
    dock: bottom;
    overflow: hidden;
    height: 1;
    background: $accent;
}


```

