### Python Textual App: Key Bindings for Dynamic Widget Creation

Source: https://textual.textualize.io/guide/input

An example Textual application demonstrating key bindings. Pressing 'r', 'g', or 'b' triggers actions to add corresponding colored 'Bar' widgets to the screen. A Footer widget displays the available bindings.

```Python
from textual.app import App, ComposeResult
from textual.color import Color
from textual.widgets import Footer, Static


class Bar(Static):
    pass


class BindingApp(App):
    """App to display key events."""

    CSS_PATH = "binding01.tcss"
    BINDINGS = [
        ("r", "add_bar('red')", "Add Red"),
        ("g", "add_bar('green')", "Add Green"),
        ("b", "add_bar('blue')", "Add Blue"),
    ]

    def compose(self) -> ComposeResult:
        yield Footer()

    def action_add_bar(self, color: str) -> None:
        bar = Bar(color)
        bar.styles.background = Color.parse(color).with_alpha(0.5)
        self.mount(bar)
        self.call_after_refresh(self.screen.scroll_end, animate=False)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    app = BindingApp()
    app.run()

```

--------------------------------

### CSS Padding Syntax

Source: https://textual.textualize.io/styles/padding

Provides CSS examples for setting padding. It demonstrates setting padding with one value (all edges), two values (top/bottom, left/right), and four values (top, right, bottom, left). Individual edge padding is also shown.

```css
/* Set padding of 1 around all edges */
padding: 1;
/* Set padding of 2 on the top and bottom edges, and 4 on the left and right */
padding: 2 4;
/* Set padding of 1 on the top, 2 on the right,
                 3 on the bottom, and 4 on the left */
padding: 1 2 3 4;

padding-top: 1;
padding-right: 2;
padding-bottom: 3;
padding-left: 4;


```

--------------------------------

### RichLog Widget API

Source: https://textual.textualize.io/widgets/rich_log

Documentation for the RichLog widget, including its attributes, methods, and usage examples.

```APIDOC
## RichLog Widget

### Description
A RichLog is a widget which displays scrollable content that may be appended to in realtime. It supports highlighting, markup, and word wrapping.

### Methods
- `write(content)`: Writes content (string or Rich renderable) to the end of the RichLog.
- `clear()`: Clears all content from the RichLog.

### Reactive Attributes

| Name | Type | Default | Description |
|---|---|---|---|
| `highlight` | `bool` | `False` | Automatically highlight content. |
| `markup` | `bool` | `False` | Apply markup. |
| `max_lines` | `int` | `None` | Maximum number of lines in the log or `None` for no maximum. |
| `min_width` | `int` | 78 | Minimum width of renderables. |
| `wrap` | `bool` | `False` | Enable word wrapping. |

### Example Usage
```python
from textual.app import App, ComposeResult
from textual.widgets import RichLog

class RichLogApp(App):
    def compose(self) -> ComposeResult:
        yield RichLog(highlight=True, markup=True)

    def on_ready(self) -> None:
        text_log = self.query_one(RichLog)
        text_log.write("[bold green]This is a log message.")
        text_log.write("Another line of text.")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    app = RichLogApp()
    app.run()
```

### Messages
This widget sends no messages.

### Bindings
This widget has no bindings.
```

