### Handle Tab Activation with 'on' Decorator and Keyword Selectors in Python

Source: https://textual.textualize.io/api/on

This example shows advanced usage of the '@on' decorator, including matching additional keyword arguments (like 'pane="#home"') to further refine which messages trigger the handler. This is useful for components with multiple states or sub-elements.

```python
from textual.widgets import TabbedContent, Tab
from textual.app import ComposeResult
from textual.screen import Screen
from textual import on

class AdvancedExampleApp(Screen):
    def compose(self) -> ComposeResult:
        yield TabbedContent(
            Tab("Home", id="home"),
            Tab("About", id="about")
        )

    @on(TabbedContent.TabActivated, "#tabs", pane="#home")
    def switch_to_home(self) -> None:
        self.log("Switching back to the home tab.")
        # ... application logic ...

```

--------------------------------

### Implement Select Widget in Textual App

Source: https://textual.textualize.io/blog/2023/05/08/textual-0240-adds-a-select-control

Demonstrates how to create a Textual application with a new Select widget. This example requires the 'textual' library and a 'select.tcss' file for styling. It handles selection changes by updating the application's title.

```python
from textual import on
from textual.app import App, ComposeResult
from textual.widgets import Header, Select

LINES = """I must not fear.
Fear is the mind-killer.
Fear is the little-death that brings total obliteration.
I will face my fear.
I will permit it to pass over me and through me.""".splitlines()


class SelectApp(App):
    CSS_PATH = "select.tcss"

    def compose(self) -> ComposeResult:
        yield Header()
        yield Select((line, line) for line in LINES)

    @on(Select.Changed)
    def select_changed(self, event: Select.Changed) -> None:
        self.title = str(event.value)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    app = SelectApp()
    app.run()

```

--------------------------------

### Basic Content Alignment Example in Python

Source: https://textual.textualize.io/styles/content_align

Demonstrates basic usage of `content-align` and specific horizontal/vertical alignment properties in a Textualize application. It shows three labels with different alignments. Requires a corresponding TCSS file for styling.

```python
from textual.app import App
from textual.widgets import Label


class ContentAlignApp(App):
    CSS_PATH = "content_align.tcss"

    def compose(self):
        yield Label("With [i]content-align[/] you can...", id="box1")
        yield Label("...[b]Easily align content[/]...", id="box2")
        yield Label("...Horizontally [i]and[/] vertically!", id="box3")


if __name__ == "__main__":
    app = ContentAlignApp()
    app.run()

```

