### Respond to Space Key Press in Textual

Source: https://textual.textualize.io/guide/input

This Python script extends the basic Textual input example by adding a specific handler for the space key. It requires the 'textual' library. When the space key is pressed, the application will emit a terminal bell sound.

```python
from textual import events
from textual.app import App, ComposeResult
from textual.widgets import RichLog


class InputApp(App):
    """App to display key events."""

    def compose(self) -> ComposeResult:
        yield RichLog()

    def on_key(self, event: events.Key) -> None:
        self.query_one(RichLog).write(event)

    def key_space(self) -> None:
        self.bell()


if __name__ == "__main__":
    app = InputApp()
    app.run()

```

--------------------------------

### Textual Layers Example (Python)

Source: https://textual.textualize.io/guide/layout

Demonstrates the use of layers to control widget drawing order in a Textual application. Widgets on higher layers are drawn on top of those on lower layers. Requires a corresponding CSS file for layer definitions.

```python
from textual.app import App, ComposeResult
from textual.widgets import Static


class LayersExample(App):
    CSS_PATH = "layers.tcss"

    def compose(self) -> ComposeResult:
        yield Static("box1 (layer = above)", id="box1")
        yield Static("box2 (layer = below)", id="box2")


if __name__ == "__main__":
    app = LayersExample()
    app.run()

```

--------------------------------

### Get Visual Height - Python

Source: https://textual.textualize.io/api/content

Calculates the height a visual element would occupy when rendered at a specific width, considering given style rules.

```python
from textual.app import App
from textual.widgets import Placeholder
from textual.containers import Container

class MyApp(App):
    def on_mount(self):
        widget = Placeholder()
        rules = widget.styles
        width = 80
        height = widget.get_height(rules, width)
        print(f"The height of the widget at width {width} is {height} lines.")

MyApp().run()
```

--------------------------------

### Basic Select Widget with Options

Source: https://textual.textualize.io/widgets/select

Demonstrates creating a Select widget with a predefined list of options. The Select widget displays a header and a dropdown list of choices. The application title updates when a selection changes. Requires the 'textual' library.

```python
from textual import on
from textual.app import App, ComposeResult
from textual.widgets import Header, Select

LINES = """I must not fear.
Fear is the mind-killer.
Fear is the little-death that brings total obliteration.
I will face my fear.
I will permit it to pass over me and through me.""".splitlines()


class SelectApp(App):
    CSS_PATH = "select.tcss"

    def compose(self) -> ComposeResult:
        yield Header()
        yield Select((line, line) for line in LINES)

    @on(Select.Changed)
    def select_changed(self, event: Select.Changed) -> None:
        self.title = str(event.value)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    app = SelectApp()
    app.run()

```

```css
Screen {
    align: center top;
}

Select {
    width: 60;
    margin: 2;
}


```

