--------------------------------

### Style Textual App for Inline Mode with CSS

Source: https://textual.textualize.io/how-to/style-inline-apps

Shows how to customize the appearance of a Textual app when running inline. This example removes the default border, increases the app height, and changes the color of the Digits widget using the :inline pseudo-selector.

```python
from datetime import datetime

from textual.app import App, ComposeResult
from textual.widgets import Digits


class ClockApp(App):
    CSS = """
    Screen {
        align: center middle;
        &:inline {
            border: none;
            height: 50vh;
            Digits {
                color: $success;
            }
        }
    }
    #clock {
        width: auto;
    }
    """

    def compose(self) -> ComposeResult:
        yield Digits("", id="clock")

    def on_ready(self) -> None:
        self.update_clock()
        self.set_interval(1, self.update_clock)

    def update_clock(self) -> None:
        clock = datetime.now().time()
        self.query_one(Digits).update(f"{clock:%T}")


if __name__ == "__main__":
    app = ClockApp()
    app.run(inline=True)

```

--------------------------------

### Get Minimal Visual Width - Python

Source: https://textual.textualize.io/api/content

Determines the minimum width required to display the content of a visual element, typically defined by the longest word.

```python
from textual.app import App
from textual.widgets import Label

class MyApp(App):
    def on_mount(self):
        label = Label("A very long word")
        rules = label.styles
        min_width = label.get_minimal_width(rules)
        print(f"The minimal width required is: {min_width} cells.")

MyApp().run()
```

