### Python Docking Syntax in Textual

Source: https://textual.textualize.io/styles/dock

Demonstrates how to apply the 'dock' style programmatically using Python in Textual. It shows the assignment of string values ('bottom', 'left', 'right', 'top') to the widget's style property.

```python
widget.styles.dock = "bottom"  # Dock bottom.
widget.styles.dock = "left"    # Dock   left.
widget.styles.dock = "right"   # Dock  right.
widget.styles.dock = "top"     # Dock    top.


```

--------------------------------

### Apply tuple padding (2 values) to Textual widgets

Source: https://textual.textualize.io/guide/styles

This example shows how to apply padding using a two-element tuple in Textual. The first value sets top/bottom padding, and the second sets left/right padding. This offers more control than a single integer for asymmetrical spacing. It utilizes `App`, `ComposeResult`, and `Static` from the `textual` library.

```python
from textual.app import App, ComposeResult
from textual.widgets import Static


TEXT = """I must not fear.
Fear is the mind-killer.
Fear is the little-death that brings total obliteration.
I will face my fear.
I will permit it to pass over me and through me.
And when it has gone past, I will turn the inner eye to see its path.
Where the fear has gone there will be nothing. Only I will remain.
"""


class PaddingApp(App):
    def compose(self) -> ComposeResult:
        self.widget = Static(TEXT)
        yield self.widget

    def on_mount(self) -> None:
        self.widget.styles.background = "purple"
        self.widget.styles.width = 30
        self.widget.styles.padding = (2, 4)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    app = PaddingApp()
    app.run()

```

--------------------------------

### SystemCommandsProvider search Method

Source: https://textual.textualize.io/api/system_commands_source

Asynchronously handles a search query for system commands within the SystemCommandsProvider. It takes a string query as input and yields command hits that match the query for use in the command palette. This allows users to efficiently find specific commands.

```python
async search(query: str)

    # Parameters:
    #    Name | Type | Description | Default
    #    --|--|--|--
    #    query | str | The user input to be matched. | _required_

    # Yields:
    #    Type | Description
    #    --|--
    #    Hits | Command hits for use in the command palette.
```

