### Get Optimal Visual Width - Python

Source: https://textual.textualize.io/api/content

Calculates the optimal width for displaying a visual element's content without unnecessary cropping or excessive whitespace, within a container's width.

```python
from textual.app import App
from textual.widgets import Label

class MyApp(App):
    def on_mount(self):
        label = Label("Short text")
        rules = label.styles
        container_width = 100
        optimal_width = label.get_optimal_width(rules, container_width)
        print(f"The optimal width is: {optimal_width} cells.")

MyApp().run()
```

--------------------------------

### Python: Initialize Placeholder with Variant Cycle

Source: https://textual.textualize.io/blog/2022/11/22/what-i-learned-from-my-first-non-trivial-pr

This Python code defines a Placeholder widget that initializes a cycle through predefined variants using `itertools.cycle`. The `__init__` method sets the initial variant and prepares the cycle for subsequent changes. The `on_click` and `cycle_variant` methods handle the logic for advancing to the next variant when the placeholder is clicked.

```python
from itertools import cycle

# Assume _VALID_PLACEHOLDER_VARIANTS_ORDERED is defined elsewhere

class Placeholder(Static):
    def __init__(
        self,
        variant: PlaceholderVariant = "default",
        *,
        label: str | None = None,
        name: str | None = None,
        id: str | None = None,
        classes: str | None = None,
    ) -> None:
        # ... (other initialization code)

        self.variant = self.validate_variant(variant)
        # Set a cycle through the variants with the correct starting point.
        self._variants_cycle = cycle(_VALID_PLACEHOLDER_VARIANTS_ORDERED)
        while next(self._variants_cycle) != self.variant:
            pass

    def on_click(self) -> None:
        """Click handler to cycle through the placeholder variants."""
        self.cycle_variant()

    def cycle_variant(self) -> None:
        """Get the next variant in the cycle."""
        self.variant = next(self._variants_cycle)

```

--------------------------------

### Utility Containers (Vertical/Horizontal) in Textual

Source: https://textual.textualize.io/guide/layout

Shows how to use Textual's `Vertical` and `Horizontal` containers to build nested layouts, creating a 2x2 grid structure. This example requires the `textual` library and its container widgets.

```python
from textual.app import App, ComposeResult
from textual.containers import Horizontal, Vertical
from textual.widgets import Static


class UtilityContainersExample(App):
    CSS_PATH = "utility_containers.tcss"

    def compose(self) -> ComposeResult:
        yield Horizontal(
            Vertical(
                Static("One"),
                Static("Two"),
                classes="column",
            ),
            Vertical(
                Static("Three"),
                Static("Four"),
                classes="column",
            ),
        )


if __name__ == "__main__":
    app = UtilityContainersExample()
    app.run()

```

```css
Static {
    content-align: center middle;
    background: crimson;
    border: solid darkred;
    height: 1fr;
}

.column {
    width: 1fr;
}

```

